SIMPLE: sex
RECORDS: 2

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Sex-
<hw>Sex-</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>. <ety>[L. <ets>sex</ets> six. See
<er>Six</er>.]</ety> <def>A combining form meaning <xex>six</xex>;
<as>as, <ex>sex</ex>digitism; <ex>sex</ex>ennial</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Sex</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Sex
<hw>Sex</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[L. <ets>sexus</ets>: cf. F.
<ets>sexe</ets>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>The distinguishing peculiarity
of male or female in both animals and plants; the physical difference
between male and female; the assemblage of properties or qualities by
which male is distinguished from female.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>One of the two divisions of organic beings formed on
the distinction of male and female.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <fld>(Bot.)</fld> <sd>(a)</sd> <def>The capability in
plants of fertilizing or of being fertilized; <as>as, staminate and
pistillate flowers are of opposite <ex>sexes</ex></as>.</def>
<sd>(b)</sd> <def>One of the groups founded on this
distinction.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>The sex</b></col>, <cd>the female sex; women, in
general.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Sexagenarian</ent>⟦br⟧
